<!--
	ws-path-independence.ptx
	Section 2 (Line Integrals and Green's Theorem), worksheet 10:
	Path Independence and Conservative Fields.

	Ported from the Beamer deck 02_03_PathIndependence.tex (in
	outdated-material/notes/, line-integrals folder): path independence,
	conservative fields, potential functions, the Fundamental Theorem of
	Line Integrals, work around closed curves, recovering a potential by
	partial antidifferentiation, and the curl test for conservativity.
	Book concepts tracked from sec_line_int_vf (Fundamental Theorem of
	Line Integrals, conservative fields, potential functions). Example
	equations are NOT reused from the deck or the book.

	This is the payoff of the identity curl(grad f) = 0 introduced in
	worksheets 7 and 9: a field with curl F = 0 is conservative, and its
	line integrals collapse to a difference of potentials.

	Authored to the SHARED worksheet conventions
	(checklists/worksheet-conventions.md): paired component="stu"/"key"
	reading checks and exercises; one True/False misconception check; one
	read-along TikZ figure; one modern application. Standard notation
	(macros from source/notes/bookends/docinfo.ptx); no new macros.
	Divergence/curl use the del operator (\nabla\cdot, \nabla\times).
	Math-valued answer keys are underlined directly (\underline{...});
	only plain-word answers are bolded, so the pdf-key (LaTeX) build stays
	clean.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-path-independence">
	<title>Path Independence and Conservative Fields</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>State what it means for a line integral to be <term>path independent</term> and for a field to be <term>conservative</term>.</li>
			<li>Apply the Fundamental Theorem of Line Integrals, <m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = f(B) - f(A)</m>, when <m>\vF = \nabla f</m>.</li>
			<li>Test whether a field is conservative using <m>\nabla\times\vF = \vzero</m>.</li>
			<li>Recover a <term>potential function</term> <m>f</m> from a conservative field by partial antidifferentiation.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: Path independence and the Fundamental Theorem
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>I. Path independence and the Fundamental Theorem.</term></p>

		<p>
			Does the work a force field does on a particle from <m>A</m> to
			<m>B</m> depend on the <em>route</em> taken? For most fields, yes.
			But a field <m>\vF</m> is called <term>conservative</term> when it
			is the gradient of some scalar <term>potential function</term>
			<m>f</m>, that is <m>\vF = \nabla f</m>. For such fields the work
			is <term>path independent</term>, and the
			<term>Fundamental Theorem of Line Integrals</term> evaluates it
			from the endpoints alone:
			<md>
				\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \int_C \nabla f\cdot d\vr = f(B) - f(A) .
			</md>
			In particular, around any <em>closed</em> curve
			(<m>A = B</m>) the work is <m>0</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="ws-pathind-fig-twopaths">
			<caption>Two different paths from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m>. For a
				conservative field both give the same work,
				<m>f(B) - f(A)</m> <ndash/> the route does not matter, only the
				endpoints.</caption>
			<image width="55%">
				<shortdescription>Two points A and B in the plane joined by two different curved paths, one bowing upward and one bowing downward, both labeled as giving the same value f(B) minus f(A).</shortdescription>
				<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1,>=stealth]
	\coordinate (A) at (0,0);
	\coordinate (B) at (4.5,1.6);
	% upper path
	\draw[very thick, blue, ->] (A) .. controls (1.2,2.4) and (3.2,2.6) .. (B);
	\node[blue] at (2.2,2.55) {$C_1$};
	% lower path
	\draw[very thick, red, ->] (A) .. controls (1.4,-0.7) and (3.4,-0.4) .. (B);
	\node[red] at (2.4,-0.75) {$C_2$};
	% endpoints
	\fill (A) circle (1.8pt) node[anchor=east] {$A$};
	\fill (B) circle (1.8pt) node[anchor=west] {$B$};
	\node at (2.3,0.9) {$\displaystyle\int_{C_1}\!\vF\cdot d\vr = \int_{C_2}\!\vF\cdot d\vr = f(B)-f(A)$};
	\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<!-- reading-check pair 1 -->
		<p component="stu">
			If <m>\vF = \nabla f</m>, the Fundamental Theorem of Line
			Integrals gives <m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = </m>
			<fillin characters="10"/>, so the work depends only on the
			<fillin characters="9"/> <nbsp/>of <m>C</m>. Around a closed curve
			the work equals <fillin characters="2"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			If <m>\vF = \nabla f</m>, the Fundamental Theorem of Line
			Integrals gives
			<m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \underline{f(B) - f(A)}</m>, so the work
			depends only on the <m>\underline{\textbf{endpoints}}</m> of
			<m>C</m>. Around a closed curve the work equals
			<m>\underline{0}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					The field <m>\vF = [\,2xy,\; x^2,\; 3z^2\,]</m> is
					conservative with potential <m>f = x^2 y + z^3</m>. Find the
					work done by <m>\vF</m> along any curve from
					<m>A(0,0,0)</m> to <m>B(1,2,1)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					The field <m>\vF = [\,2xy,\; x^2,\; 3z^2\,]</m> is
					conservative with potential <m>f = x^2 y + z^3</m>. Find the
					work done by <m>\vF</m> along any curve from
					<m>A(0,0,0)</m> to <m>B(1,2,1)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					By the Fundamental Theorem of Line Integrals we only need
					the endpoints:
					<md>
						W = \int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = f(B) - f(A)
						= f(1,2,1) - f(0,0,0) .
					</md>
					Since <m>f(1,2,1) = (1)^2(2) + (1)^3 = 3</m> and
					<m>f(0,0,0) = 0</m>, the work is <m>W = 3</m>. No
					parametrization of <m>C</m> was needed <ndash/> any path
					from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> gives the same answer.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: The conservative test
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>II. Testing whether a field is conservative.</term></p>

		<p>
			Hunting for a potential is a poor way to <em>decide</em> whether
			one exists. Fortunately there is a quick test. Because
			<m>\nabla\times(\nabla f) = \vzero</m> always (worksheet 9), a
			conservative field must have zero curl. On a domain with no holes
			the converse holds too, giving the
			<term>conservative test</term>: <m>\vF = [\,M,N,P\,]</m> is
			conservative exactly when
			<md>
				\nabla\times\vF = \vzero,
				\qquad\text{i.e.}\qquad
				P_y = N_z, \quad M_z = P_x, \quad N_x = M_y .
			</md>
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 2 -->
		<p component="stu">
			A field <m>\vF = [\,M,N,P\,]</m> is conservative exactly when its
			curl is <fillin characters="3"/>; equivalently
			<m>P_y = </m> <fillin characters="4"/>, <m>M_z = </m>
			<fillin characters="4"/>, and <m>N_x = </m>
			<fillin characters="4"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			A field <m>\vF = [\,M,N,P\,]</m> is conservative exactly when its
			curl is <m>\underline{\vzero}</m>; equivalently
			<m>P_y = \underline{N_z}</m>, <m>M_z = \underline{P_x}</m>, and
			<m>N_x = \underline{M_y}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Determine whether <m>\vF = [\,2xy^3,\; 3x^2 y^2,\; 1\,]</m>
					is conservative.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Determine whether <m>\vF = [\,2xy^3,\; 3x^2 y^2,\; 1\,]</m>
					is conservative.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					With <m>M = 2xy^3</m>, <m>N = 3x^2 y^2</m>, <m>P = 1</m>,
					check the three equalities:
					<md>
						<mrow>P_y \amp = 0 = N_z, </mrow>
						<mrow>M_z \amp = 0 = P_x, </mrow>
						<mrow>N_x \amp = 6xy^2 = M_y .</mrow>
					</md>
					All three hold, so <m>\nabla\times\vF = \vzero</m> and
					<m>\vF</m> <em>is</em> conservative. (We will build its
					potential on the next page.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Determine whether <m>\vF = [\,y,\; 3x,\; 0\,]</m> is
					conservative.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Determine whether <m>\vF = [\,y,\; 3x,\; 0\,]</m> is
					conservative.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Here <m>M = y</m>, <m>N = 3x</m>, <m>P = 0</m>. The first
					two equalities hold (<m>P_y = 0 = N_z</m> and
					<m>M_z = 0 = P_x</m>), but the third fails:
					<md>
						N_x = 3 \neq 1 = M_y .
					</md>
					Since <m>N_x \neq M_y</m>, the curl is not <m>\vzero</m>,
					so <m>\vF</m> is <em>not</em> conservative <ndash/> no
					potential function exists.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: Recovering a potential function
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>III. Recovering a potential function.</term></p>

		<p>
			Once a field passes the test, we can build its potential. Writing
			<m>\nabla f = \vF = [\,M,N,P\,]</m> means
			<m>f_x = M</m>, <m>f_y = N</m>, <m>f_z = P</m>. Antidifferentiate
			<m>f_x = M</m> in <m>x</m> (the <q>constant</q> of integration is
			a function <m>g(y,z)</m>), then differentiate that result in
			<m>y</m> and match <m>N</m> to pin down <m>g</m>, and finally
			match <m>P</m> to finish. Each step recovers a little more of
			<m>f</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 3 -->
		<p component="stu">
			To recover <m>f</m> from <m>\nabla f = \vF</m> we take partial
			<fillin characters="14"/> <nbsp/>one variable at a time,
			introducing at each step an unknown
			<fillin characters="8"/> <nbsp/>of the remaining variables.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			To recover <m>f</m> from <m>\nabla f = \vF</m> we take partial
			<m>\underline{\textbf{antiderivatives}}</m> one variable at a
			time, introducing at each step an unknown
			<m>\underline{\textbf{function}}</m> of the remaining variables.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="3in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find a potential function for the (conservative) field
					<m>\vF = [\,2xy^3,\; 3x^2 y^2,\; 1\,]</m> from page 2.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find a potential function for the (conservative) field
					<m>\vF = [\,2xy^3,\; 3x^2 y^2,\; 1\,]</m> from page 2.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					We need <m>f</m> with <m>f_x = 2xy^3</m>,
					<m>f_y = 3x^2 y^2</m>, <m>f_z = 1</m>. Antidifferentiate the
					first in <m>x</m>:
					<md>
						f = x^2 y^3 + g(y,z) .
					</md>
					Then <m>f_y = 3x^2 y^2 + g_y</m> must equal
					<m>3x^2 y^2</m>, so <m>g_y = 0</m> and <m>g = h(z)</m>.
					Now <m>f = x^2 y^3 + h(z)</m>, and <m>f_z = h_z</m> must
					equal <m>1</m>, so <m>h = z</m> (taking the constant to be
					<m>0</m>). Therefore
					<md>
						f = x^2 y^3 + z .
					</md>
					A quick check: <m>\nabla f = [\,2xy^3,\,3x^2y^2,\,1\,] = \vF</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="3in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Verify that <m>\vF = [\,y+2x,\; x+z,\; y\,]</m> is
					conservative, then find a potential function for it.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Verify that <m>\vF = [\,y+2x,\; x+z,\; y\,]</m> is
					conservative, then find a potential function for it.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					With <m>M = y+2x</m>, <m>N = x+z</m>, <m>P = y</m>:
					<m>P_y = 1 = N_z</m>, <m>M_z = 0 = P_x</m>,
					<m>N_x = 1 = M_y</m>, so <m>\vF</m> is conservative.
					Antidifferentiate <m>f_x = y + 2x</m> in <m>x</m>:
					<m>f = xy + x^2 + g(y,z)</m>. Then
					<m>f_y = x + g_y = x + z</m> forces <m>g_y = z</m>, so
					<m>g = yz + h(z)</m>. Now
					<m>f = xy + x^2 + yz + h(z)</m>, and <m>f_z = y + h_z = y</m>
					gives <m>h_z = 0</m>. Hence
					<md>
						f = x^2 + xy + yz .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: A misconception, an application, and looking ahead
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>IV. A caution and an application.</term></p>

		<!-- misconception check: single exercise, solution instructor-only -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-pathind-tf-parametrize">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<alert>True or False.</alert> To compute
					<m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m> for a conservative field
					<m>\vF</m>, you must first find a parametrization of the
					path <m>C</m>. Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					<term>False.</term> That is exactly the advantage of a
					conservative field. Once <m>\vF = \nabla f</m>, the
					Fundamental Theorem gives
					<m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = f(B) - f(A)</m>, which uses only
					the endpoints <ndash/> <em>no parametrization is needed</em>,
					and indeed we need not even know which path <m>C</m> is.
					(For a <em>non</em>-conservative field the value genuinely
					depends on the path, and then a parametrization is
					required.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>An application.</term></p>

		<!-- application (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Near the ground, gravity on a mass <m>m</m> is the constant
					field <m>\vF = [\,0,\,0,\,-mg\,]</m>. Show it is
					conservative by exhibiting a potential, and find the work
					gravity does as the mass moves from height <m>z = 0</m> to
					height <m>z = h</m> along <em>any</em> path.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Near the ground, gravity on a mass <m>m</m> is the constant
					field <m>\vF = [\,0,\,0,\,-mg\,]</m>. Show it is
					conservative by exhibiting a potential, and find the work
					gravity does as the mass moves from height <m>z = 0</m> to
					height <m>z = h</m> along <em>any</em> path.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Take <m>f = -mgz</m>; then
					<m>\nabla f = [\,0,\,0,\,-mg\,] = \vF</m>, so gravity is
					conservative. By the Fundamental Theorem, moving from a
					point at height <m>0</m> to one at height <m>h</m>,
					<md>
						W = f(\text{top}) - f(\text{bottom})
						= -mgh - 0 = -mgh ,
					</md>
					<em>regardless of the trail</em> taken. This is why the
					work against gravity to climb a hill of height <m>h</m>
					depends only on <m>h</m>, not on whether the path is a
					short steep scramble or a long gentle switchback. (For
					<m>m = 70</m> kg and <m>h = 100</m> m, gravity does about
					<m>-6.9\times 10^4</m> J of work.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<p>
				<alert>Looking ahead.</alert> Conservative fields are the
				well-behaved ones: zero curl, path-independent work, a
				potential, and no work around a closed loop. But most fields
				are <em>not</em> conservative, and then the work around a
				closed loop is generally nonzero. Measuring that leftover
				circulation is the job of <term>Green's Theorem</term>, next:
				it equates the circulation of a field around a closed curve in
				the plane with the total curl integrated over the region the
				curve encloses.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>

</worksheet>
